{"Body": "<p>The Church of Ireland Archbishop of Dublin has ardently objected to the Government&rsquo;s plans to cut funding for three teacher-training colleges last week in his presidential address to the Dublin and Glendalough synod.</p>\n<p>In an Irish Times article published last week, Dr Neill criticised the Government&rsquo;s plans to cut funding for the teacher training colleges. He accused the Government of mounting a &ldquo;very determined and doctrinaire effort &hellip; to strike at a sector which some officials totally failed to understand&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>Marino Institute of Education, Froebel College and Church of Ireland College of Education are three teacher-training colleges affiliated to Trinity College. The Government announced last month that they planned to phase out funding for these teaching colleges.</p>\n<p>This proposal was strongly backed by the Department of Finance as the deemed it necessary to make many cuts to third level education as a means to make amends to the Irish economy.</p>\n<p>Dr. Pauric Travers, president of St. Patrick&rsquo;s College, also criticized the Government&rsquo;s plans in a parliamentary debate in the D&aacute;il last April. Dr Travers told the D&aacute;il that &ldquo;there is an effective system of internal financial control to ensure efficiency and effectiveness in respect of expenditure of public funds, as set out in the financial statements&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>Dr Travers firmly pointed out to the D&aacute;il that &ldquo;there has been relatively little capital investment in the colleges of education in recent decades&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>He highlighted the fact that in the absence of State funding, Marino embarked on a significant campus development for essential facilities which was funded through borrowings.</p>\n<p>Dr Travers also saw no logic in cuts to the teaching colleges, but stressed further that the Government had a duty to continue funding these colleges, &ldquo;despite the difficult financial times&rdquo;. He went on further persuade the Government that they would not gain anything by cutting teaching colleges as it would lead to a shortage in primary school teachers and a demand for more teaching colleges in the future.</p>", "Imageurl": "<p>The Church of Ireland Archbishop of Dublin has ardently objected to the Government&rsquo;s plans to cut funding for three teacher-training colleges last week in his presidential address to the Dublin and Glendalough synod.</p>\n<p>In an Irish Times article published last week, Dr Neill criticised the Government&rsquo;s plans to cut funding for the teacher training colleges. He accused the Government of mounting a &ldquo;very determined and doctrinaire effort &hellip; to strike at a sector which some officials totally failed to understand&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>Marino Institute of Education, Froebel College and Church of Ireland College of Education are three teacher-training colleges affiliated to Trinity College. The Government announced last month that they planned to phase out funding for these teaching colleges.</p>\n<p>This proposal was strongly backed by the Department of Finance as the deemed it necessary to make many cuts to third level education as a means to make amends to the Irish economy.</p>\n<p>Dr. Pauric Travers, president of St. Patrick&rsquo;s College, also criticized the Government&rsquo;s plans in a parliamentary debate in the D&aacute;il last April. Dr Travers told the D&aacute;il that &ldquo;there is an effective system of internal financial control to ensure efficiency and effectiveness in respect of expenditure of public funds, as set out in the financial statements&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>Dr Travers firmly pointed out to the D&aacute;il that &ldquo;there has been relatively little capital investment in the colleges of education in recent decades&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>He highlighted the fact that in the absence of State funding, Marino embarked on a significant campus development for essential facilities which was funded throug